   "source": [
    "## Unit 3: Building a Rods Data Model\n",
    "\n",
    "To model the Rod domain as a `data type` we ask two questions\n",
    "\n",
    "  * what is the data?\n",
    "  * what is its structure?\n",
    "\n",
    "## What is the data?\n",
    "\n",
    "If we just consider the collection of rods without the constructions (such as trains) then the `data` are the names that we choose for each rod. \n",
    "\n",
    "   * A rod may for example have a colour name (which is not unique, all rods of the same colour have the same name)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## What is the structure?\n",
    "\n",
    "To model the *structure* we consider the kinds of relationship possible between two arbitrary rods: that is, they may be the same length or different lengths. \n",
    "\n",
    "This relationship is technically known as a __partial order__. \n",
    "\n",
    " * We will therefore need a way of checking if two rods are the same length, or different lengths.\n",
    "      * We will get this by implementing the `Ord` type class\n",
    "\n",
    "The `Colour` data type consists of 10 different names, or `constructors`, listed in order, one for each colour.\n",
    "\n",
    "`Implementing` type classes gives our rods some special abilities! What abilities are these?\n",
    "\n",
    "* Implementing `Eq` allows us to compare two instances of a `Colour` to see if they are the same with the `==` predicate\n",
    "* `Ord` makes our data ordered! `Red < Yellow`, `Purple > Black`, `Yellow <= Yellow`. \n",
    "* `Enum` makes our type enumerable! `Red` is the successor or `White`, `Purple` is the successor of `Green` and so on!\n",
    "* Implementing the `Show` type class permits us to `print` something of the type `Colour`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "-- First of all, we model the properties of the rods with their Gattegno Colour \n",
    "-- names as a \"sum\" type instantiating the type classes Show, Eq, Ord and Enum\n",
    "data Colour = White \n",
    "            | Red \n",
    "            | Green \n",
    "            | Pink \n",
    "            | Yellow \n",
    "            | DarkGreen \n",
    "            | Black \n",
    "            | Brown \n",
    "            | Blue \n",
    "            | Orange \n",
    "            deriving (Show, Eq, Ord, Enum) "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Below we have written a function that accepts any colour value, and converts it to its rod length measured with a White. The variable `colour`, of type Colour specified in the type signature matches any valid Colour constructor."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Brown"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "succ DarkGreen"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "rodLength :: Colour -> Int  -- this is the type signature\n",
    "rodLength White = 1 \n",
    "rodLength colour = 1 + rodLength (pred colour)"
   ]
